The “miraculous” recovery of a survivor student of the Peshawar massacre
A teenager paralyzed after being shot four times in the worst terrorist attack in Pakistan was able to recover “miraculous” after treatment in the United Kingdom.
Mohamed Ibrahim Khan, 13 years of age, the doctors in Pakistan had told him he would never be able to go again.
At least 140 people, most children, were killed when armed men attacked the public school of the Peshawar army last December.
Mohamed, who arrived in London last month for surgery, will be later released from the hospital.
Exactly nine months ago, in the usual morning of Tuesday, Mohamed was sitting at first aid hour and listening to his teachers.
Right then, seven armed men dressed in the uniforms of security officers entered the public school of the army.
They wore belts with explosives and had to carry out a simple mission: to kill all the men, women and children on their way.
"I can't forget what happened that day," says Mohamed with a rough look.
I was sitting in the amphitheater, asking questions... then I heard gunshots outside.
The terrorists went inside and started killing. Our professor was burned alive.
Mohamed describes how he pulled four students out of the amphitheater while the carnage was taking place.
Then he says he heard his friend, Hamza, screaming him.
He said, "Oh, man, save me."
I held him by the hand.
Then I was shot in the back, and he was in the head.
Most of the people who were killed in the attack were students
Hamza died in Mohamed's arms.
Mohamed recalls that immediately after that he passed out and that the next thing he knew was that he was on a hospital bed, paralyzed from the blue down.
The doctors in Peshawar in northern Pakistan, then those in Rawalpindi, near the capital, told his family that there was no treatment and that he would never be able to go.
"When I saw him, I felt my soul coming out," says Sher Khan, Mohamed's father.
Those nine months were the hardest in my life.
But Khan and his wife, Sherbano, refused to believe that their son so passionate about cricket would never be able to use his legs again.
They campaigned and asked for help from Pakistani television, attracting the support of famous people like Imran Khan, a crichet player becoming a politician.
In the end, they managed to raise funds to take Mohamed to the United Kingdom and offer him treatment at the Harley Street private clinic in London.
The consultant neurosurgeon Irfan Malik described Mohamed as "afraid" when he arrived at the hospital.
“He had spent his last few months lying in bed, without being able to move from one side to the other, ” says Malik.
He was weak, he put a lot of pressure on his back.
He wasn't in a very good shape.
A vertebrae at the base of Mohamed's spine had been destroyed
Mohamed had been shot in his shoulder, hip, and back during the attack, and his lower spine had been destroyed, leading to paralysis.
However, during an operation that lasted six hours, Malik and his team managed to reconnect the nerve endings and rebuild the destroyed part of the column.
Even Malik was surprised by what happened next.
Just one week after the operation, Mohamed got up and started taking steps and going.
We weren't expecting such a good outcome.
It was a miracle," he says.
Within two weeks of the operation, Mohamed is ready to leave the hospital and start the long recovery process.
Mohamed challenged fate and began to walk again
He wants to become strong and to continue his studies in the United Kingdom.
But he is determined to return to Pakistan, to join the army and to fight terrorism.
"I feel like I still have a chance to live," he says, showing pictures with weapons drawn by him near school manuals and pens
Physically, Mohamed gets stronger every day, but psychological trauma through which he passes and now is unimaginable.
"My fury has not fallen," he confesses.
In my school little kids were killed.
What murder did they commit?
His mother wipes out a tear, comforts him, and says: “I see my son walking again. ”
He'll be able to continue his life.
