I think I'm extremely lucky to have him in the open.
You remixed albums of troops like XTC, Tears for Fears and Yes.
How much does that affect your own music?
I am not consciously inspired by this, but, inevitably, when you deconstruct these classic albums, they remain in your mind.
My last solo album, The Raven That Refused to Sing, was undoubtedly the most progressive old school album I ever created.
I don't think it was a coincidence that I remixed King Crimson, Jethro Tull and Yes almost all year before.
The current album, Hand. Erase., is much more open, because I was working at Tears for Fears and XTC.
You are often described as the busiest progressive rock musician.
That's how you feel?
You can remove the word progressively.
I think I'm probably one of the most obsessed people in today's music world and I'm not saying that proudly, because, please believe me, it's a curse.
I think I inherited this from my father, who has an incredibly strong work ethic.
If I don't do anything a whole day, I'm starting to feel guilty.
That's why remix work was a gift, because it means I don't have to do all the time just my music.
The music industry is a tough place to make your career.
Now I wouldn't recommend this to anyone as a profession.
I work every day and I'm not rich, but I live well.
I love what I do, it's a privilege, but if I were lazy I don't think I would have survived.
