Most of the deaths caused by air rain are caused by tiny particles, which can be inhaled deep into the lungs.
They cause heart attack and stroke, which are responsible for three quarters of the 3.3 million deaths annually, while the rest are caused by lung cancer and respiratory diseases.
Research has not included the effects of indoor air pollution, e.g. from cooking fires, which are estimated to cause 3.4 million more deaths per year.
The new study, published in Nature newspaper, is the first to highlight various sources of outdoor air pollution and estimated the number of premature deaths they cause, taking into account road traffic, fossil fuel power plants and other sources.
Researchers used a detailed computerized model of the global atmosphere to evaluate the impact of air pollution on different populations, including new information on how they affect pollution on Chinese and Indian inhabitants.
One third of all premature deaths were the result of the use of smoke-extinguishing fuels, such as wood and coal, for the heating of dwellings or cooking, and of the use of dirty diesel generators for electricity, all of these are recognised dangers.
The consumption of this type of internal energy causes half of India’s 645 000 annual deaths and one third of China’s 1.4 million annual deaths.
However, the research found that agricultural ammonia emissions had a "significant" impact, according to Professor Jos Lelieveld of the German Chemical Max Planck Institute, which conducted the research.
One fifth of the global deaths are caused by these emissions, which mainly come from cattle, birds and pigs and from over-use of fertilizers.
Ammonia reacts with exhaust gases from traffic and industry and produces tiny particles, being the main cause of deaths due to air pollution from eastern USA, Japan and Europe.
"For London, agriculture is the main source," says Lelieveld.
Throughout the United Kingdom, 48% of premature deaths were the result of agricultural pollution.
Traffic pollution is still an important factor in developed countries, causing a fifth of the deaths, despite measures against polluting vehicles.
This has caused only 5% of deaths globally, but the figure could increase as more and more cars appear on the streets in developing countries.
Air pollution by the power plant, in particular by those operating with coal, was significant globally, causing one of seven deaths.
In the United States it is the main single factor, causing one third of the 55 000 deaths per year, compared to 16% in the United Kingdom.
Natural air pollution, especially in arid and dusty regions, has caused almost a fifth of the global deaths caused by air pollution.
This source is a major factor in some arid countries, accounting for 92% of deaths in Egypt and 81% in Iran.
"The supposition between the high degree of pollution and the large number of inhabitants speaks to them about public health, but there is no longer any knowledge of the sources of pollution responsible for premature deaths," says Jerrett.
The results are surprising and potentially important for the protection of public health at global level.
Currently all particles are supposed to be as toxic.
But if those caused by fuel burning are more toxic, as some scientists suspect, the percentage of premature deaths that can be attributed to agricultural emissions would be lower.
Even so, Jerrett says "discovery is very valuable... because agriculture has not generally been seen as a major source of air pollution or premature death and suggests that much more attention should be paid to agricultural sources, both from scientists and political leaders."
