Coral reefs are seriously at risk of decline (WWF) Some marine habitats, such as mangroves and sea grass, which depend on many other species, have experienced a significant decline, while the entire population of commercially valued fish, such as macro and tuna, have dropped vertiginos by three quarters compared to the 1970s, the report shows.
Many coral reefs, usually described as tropical forests of the oceans due to their huge biodiversity, could be threatened with extinction until the middle of this century if the acidity of the ocean continues to deteriorate, as a result of increased levels of CO2 in the atmosphere, causing direct proportional increase in the level of carbonic acid from the sea.
"Healthy seas are a source of extraordinary beauty and natural wonder and are also a basis for the functioning of the global economy," said Louise Heaps, a chief marine policy adviser at WWF-UK, who contributed to the preparation of the report.
"By overfishing, which damage coastal habitats, and without solving the global warming problem, we are like the seeds of an ecological economic catastrophe," says Dr. Heaps.
The report, based on a review of published scientific literature, and also on the indexes of the living planet, a database maintained by the London Zoo, is one of the most detailed studies on marine life ever undertaken.
Nearly 20% of the total mangrove areas disappeared between 1980 and 2005 (WWF) It investigated a wide variety of marine species, from fish, sea turtles and sea cucumbers - an animal similar to a worm, with rough skin - to marine plants such as mangroves and algae.
The report found that the algae areas decreased by about 30% in the last century, while the total mangrove areas decreased by 20% between 1980 and 2005, mainly as a result of shrimp fishing and other forms of aquaculture.
Over a single generation, human activity has caused enormous damage to the ocean, catching fish faster than it can reproduce and also destroying their banks.
There is a need for profound changes in order to ensure abundant ocean life in the next generations," said Marco Lambertini, director general of WWF International.
Some of the most dramatic declines have occurred in species fishing for commercial profits.
For example, 58 populations from 17 species belonging to the Scrumbidae family - macro, ton and sardines - fell by 74% between 1970 and 2010, without giving signs of recovery, the report says.
We are in a fishing race that could end up depriving people of a vital food source and an essential economic engine.
Overfishing, destruction of marine habitats and climate change have serious consequences for the entire human population, and poor communities, which are based on the sea, will be hit the fastest and most powerful," Lambertini said.
"The collapse of ocean ecosystems could trigger a serious economic decline and could undermine our fight to eradicate poverty and undernutrition," he continued.
Professor Ken Norris, ZL Scientific Director, said: "These alarming figures show how quickly people change plants and animals in the ocean and represent a clear warning about the problems we could face as a result."
Sea grass: deep underwater “pests” that catch rich sediments in minerals and stabilize the bottom of the sea.
During the last century, the surface covered decreased by 30%.
Mangrove: their existence is known in 123 countries, almost half of the total area representing only five countries.
Nearly 20% of all mangrove areas disappeared between 1980 and 2005, mainly due to human invasion.
Coral reefs: some of the richest and most biologically productive habitats on earth.
One quarter of all marine species live in or near coral reefs, but three quarters of them are currently threatened and many can disappear during this century if the acidity of the ocean continues to deteriorate.
In-depth habitats: very little is known about the deep-sea areas, but the decline in the amount of fish caught in these inaccessible locations over the past 40 years suggests that they are also affected by global marine changes.
