In 210 of children whose mothers had been treated against SSRI depression, there was no increased risk of behavioural problems compared with 231 children who were more prone to behavioural problems such as hyperactivity, lack of attention and socialization.
The same group of Australian researchers also found in a separate study that mothers are more likely to bleed after birth if treated with SSRI.
Analysis of medical data from 30 198 who were born at a university hospital in Adelaide between 2002 and 2008 showed that the risk of postnatal haemorrhage increased by 5% between 11 and 16% if women were treated with SSRI.
The risk of severe haemorrhage or postnatal anaemia has doubled, researchers have reported.
