"It is possible that women who took antidepressants at an advanced stage of pregnancy were those with the most serious stage of the disease, and this is the reason for the increased risk of postnatal haemorrhage, not antidepressants," says Dr. Luke Grzeskowiak, professor at Adelaide University.
